n    - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24\n    - ifconfig shows RX packets 0, TX packets 0 (no observed L2 traffic in the snapshot).\n    - ip route: default via 10.0.0.1 dev eth0.\n  - leaf_router_0_0:\n    - eth2: inet 10.0.0.1/24 (this is the leaf->host interface)\n    - eth2 ifconfig shows RX packets 0, TX packets 0 (no observed L2 traffic on the leaf side of the host link).\n    - eth0, eth1 (inter-router links) show traffic and are UP.\n  - pc_0_1 and leaf_router_0_1 show non-zero TX/RX on their host-facing interfaces → that host/pod is operating normally.\n- Routing / BGP state:\n  - BGP is present and advertising host prefixes across the fabric. Examples:\n    - super_spine_router_0 BGP table shows 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 with valid paths.\n    - spine_router and other leaves have entries for 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24.\n  - Abnormal route on leaf_router_0_0:\n    - The kernel route table for leaf_router_0_0 shows a static blackhole route for 10.0.0.0/30 (line present in the ip route output: \"blackhole 10.0.0.0/30 proto static metric 20\" and \"S>* 10.0.0.0/30 [1/0] unreachable (blackhole) ...\").\n    - Note: 10.0.0.0/30 is more specific than 10.0.0.0/24 and would match hosts whose addresses fall in that /30 (10.0.0.0–10.0.0.3), which includes 10.0.0.2 (pc_0_0).\n  - leaf_router_0_0 also shows 10.0.0.0/24 as directly connected on eth2; therefore both a connected /24 and a static blackhole /30 coexist in the routing table; the more specific blackhole will be selected for addresses inside the /30.\n\n3) Anomalies identified\n- Layer-2 symptom: host-facing interfaces for the affected pair show zero RX/TX counters (pc_0_0 eth0: 0/0; leaf_router_0_0 eth2: 0/0). That indicates no L2 traffic observed on that host link at the time of snapshot.\n- Routing anomaly on leaf_router_0_0: a static blackhole route for 10.0.0.0/30 is present and is more specific than the connected /24. This will cause traffic to addresses within that /30 to be blackholed (dropped) by the router's forwarding plane.\n- Control plane vs data plane inconsistency: BGP is converged and other prefixes are reachable via the fabric, but traffic to pc_0_0 fails — indicates local data‑plane or local-routing issue on the leaf or link rather than global convergence problem.\n\n4) Localization — where the fault(s) appear to be\nPrimary localized components (highest likelihood):\n- leaf_router_0_0:\n  - Evidence: routing table contains a blackhole route that would drop traffic destined to 10.0.0.2; eth2 has zero packet counters while eth0/eth1 show activity; BGP is present but local forwarding is anomalous.\n- link/interface between leaf_router_0_0:eth2 and pc_0_0:eth0:\n  - Evidence: both ends show 0 RX/TX on host-facing interfaces. ping from pc_0_0 to leaf_router_0_0 fails.\nSecondary (lower likelihood but possible):\n- pc_0_0 itself (misconfigured or interface problem):\n  - Evidence: eth0 has correct IP and route, but interface counters 0. Could be that PC interface is administratively up but physical cable disconnected or VM NIC not attached.\n\n5) Probable root cause(s) (ranked with rationale)\n- Root cause candidate A (high confidence): Misconfigured/accidental static blackhole route on leaf_router_0_0 covering 10.0.0.0/30 (more specific) — this would cause the router to drop traffic for host addresses in that /30 (including pc_0_0's address 10.0.0.2). Evidence: explicit blackhole route present in the leaf_router_0_0 route table; specificity (/30) would override /24 connected route.\n  - Impact explanation: packets destined for 10.0.0.2 arriving at leaf_router_0_0 (from elsewhere) will be discarded. That explains the reachability from remote hosts. It does not fully explain why L2 counters are zero on the leaf-facing interface, but can explain host-unreachability from other nodes.\n- Root cause candidate B (medium confidence): Layer-2/link failure or disconnected link between pc_0_0 and leaf_router_0_0 (cable/virtual NIC down or miswired). Evidence: both pc_0_0 eth0 and leaf_router_0_0 eth2 counters show zero RX/TX; pc_0_0 cannot reach the network. This would prevent ARP and any host-side traffic to leave/arrive, causing the observed 100% loss. This could be independent of (or co-occurring with) the blackhole route.\n- Combined hypothesis (both A and B): Both a local blackhole route and a link-level problem exist. The blackhole explains drops seen from the wider fabric; the link-level problem explains the zero counters and host inability to reach its gateway at L2. The data supports both anomalies being present on leaf_router_0_0.\n\n6) Impact / affected components\n- Affected host: pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2) — fully unreachable from pc_0_1 and likely unreachable from the rest of the fabric.\n- Affected router: leaf_router_0_0 (local forwarding for 10.0.0.0/30).\n- The rest of the fabric (spines, super-spine, leaf_router_0_1, pc_0_1) appears healthy (BGP converged and traffic on those links is OK).\n\n7) Confidence levels\n- Blackhole route on leaf_router_0_0 being problematic: high confidence (explicit route present and would match the host IP).\n- L2/link issue between pc_0_0 and leaf_router_0_0: medium confidence (0 counters on both ends strongly suggest link-layer issue, but concurrent timing/measurement artifacts are possible).\n- Global BGP/fabric issue causing the outage: low confidence (BGP tables show both /24s advertised and present).\n\n8) Useful follow-up diagnostic commands (for validation — not mitigation)\n- On leaf_router_0_0:\n  - show ip route 10.0.0.0/30 and show ip route 10.0.0.0/24 to confirm selection and metrics.\n  - show running-config (or FRR BGP config) and check for static route/blackhole statements for 10.0.0.0/30.\n  - ip neigh / arp table and show interface eth2 status (ethtool) to confirm link state and MAC/ARP behavior.\n  - show log/syslog for any interface flaps or route changes.\n- On pc_0_0:\n  - arp -n, ip neigh, ethtool eth0 (or equivalent) to check link/phy, and check interface attach state in hypervisor if virtualized.\n  - Attempt ping to local gateway 10.0.0.1 (L2 test) and capture any ARP requests on leaf_router_0_0 (tcpdump) to see if frames arrive.\n- On another router (spine/super-spine):\n  - traceroute towards 10.0.0.2 to show at which hop packets disappear.\n  - show ip route to confirm whether remote routers send traffic toward leaf_router_0_0 and which next-hop they select.\n\n9) Final assessment (brief)\n- There is an active outage for pc_0_0. The strongest, immediate indicators are:\n  1) leaf_router_0_0 has a static blackhole route for 10.0.0.0/30 (more specific than its connected /24) — this alone can cause dropped traffic to 10.0.0.2 from the fabric.\n  2) Host-facing L2 counters for pc_0_0 <-> leaf_router_0_0 are zero, indicating a possible physical/link-layer disconnect or that traffic is not being forwarded at L2 on that port.\n- The issue is localized to leaf_router_0_0 and its host-facing link. Further diagnostics (commands above) should be executed to confirm whether the primary cause is the blackhole route, a physical link problem, or both.\n\nIf you want, I can run additional targeted checks now (arp tables, ethtool, show ip route for the specific prefixes, FRR running-config on leaf_router_0_0, or tcpdump on the leaf's eth2) to narrow the root cause further., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.\nAI: \nTool: [\"dns_record_error\", \"host_crash\", \"host_ip_conflict\", \"host_incorrect_dns\", \"host_incorrect_gateway\", \"host_incorrect_ip\", \"host_incorrect_netmask\", \"host_missing_ip\", \"dhcp_service_down\", \"dns_service_down\", \"host_vpn_membership_missing\", \"link_detach\", \"link_down\", \"link_flap\", \"link_fragmentation_disabled\", \"arp_acl_block\", \"bgp_acl_block\", \"dns_port_blocked\", \"http_acl_block\", \"icmp_acl_block\", \"ospf_acl_block\", \"bgp_asn_misconfig\", \"bgp_blackhole_route_leak\", \"bgp_hijacking\", \"bgp_missing_route_advertisement\", \"host_static_blackhole\", \"dhcp_missing_subnet\", \"mac_address_conflict\", \"ospf_area_misconfiguration\", \"ospf_neighbor_missing\", \"p4_aggressive_detection_thresholds\", \"flow_rule_loop\", \"flow_rule_shadowing\", \"sdn_controller_crash\", \"southbound_port_block\", \"southbound_port_mismatch\", \"p4_header_definition_error\", \"p4_compilation_error_parser_state\", \"mpls_label_limit_exceeded\", \"p4_table_entry_misconfig\", \"p4_table_entry_missing\", \"bmv2_switch_down\", \"frr_service_down\", \"arp_cache_poisoning\", \"dhcp_spoofed_dns\", \"dhcp_spoofed_gateway\", \"web_dos_attack\", \"link_bandwidth_throttling\", \"link_high_packet_corruption\", \"link_queue_overflow\", \"dns_lookup_latency\", \"load_balancer_overload\"]\nAI: \nTool: Submission success."], "metadata": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
{"timestamp": "2025-11-28 16:26:51.072797", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Submission completed.\n\nSummary of submitted solution:\n- is_anomaly: true\n- faulty_devices: [\"leaf_router_0_0\", \"pc_0_0\"]\n- root_cause_name: [\"host_static_blackhole\", \"link_down\"]\n\nRecommended immediate remediation steps (not part of submission but suggested):\n1. On leaf_router_0_0, remove or correct the static blackhole for 10.0.0.0/30 (verify FRR/static route config) so the connected /24 is preferred for host traffic.\n2. Verify and restore the physical/virtual link between pc_0_0 and leaf_router_0_0:\n   - Check interface state and counters (ethtool, ip link), reconnect cable or reattach VM NIC if necessary.\n   - Run tcpdump on leaf_router_0_0 eth2 to confirm ARP/ICMP traffic from pc_0_0 once link is restored.\n3. After fixing, validate:\n   - From pc_0_0: ping 10.0.0.1 and pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2).\n   - From leaf_router_0_0: confirm no blackhole route exists for the host and that route selection uses connected 10.0.0.0/24.\n\nIf you want, I can run targeted diagnostics now (show ip route, running-config, ethtool, tcpdump) to validate and walk through the remediation.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 3211, "output_tokens": 303, "total_tokens": 3514, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 2688}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 0}}}
